<H2>Depression and Healthcare Use</H2>
<HR>
	According to a study in the October Archives of General Psychiatry, depression doubles healthcare use.  The study of 6,000 
depressed patients in a Seattle HMO found that they make twice as many general medical and specialty visits, incur double the pharmacy 
costs, and use twice as many lab, radiology, and other services as persons without depression.  Only 20 percent of the visits were for mental 
illness.
